{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536763"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:09:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:09:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15809"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15809"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.07,0.28,0.32,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8500"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104846"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8500"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15809"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87232"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"2793"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20414"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38020"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38021"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104846"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe junior doctor on the medical ward is called to review a 72-year-old woman for hyperkalaemia noted on routine blood tests. She was admitted two days ago following an acute stroke. She has a history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, and chronic kidney disease. Her medications include metformin, ramipril and atorvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 138/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 5.7 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine 156 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrea 12.2 mmol/L (2.5-7.8).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EECG: normal sinus rhythm with no acute changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nebulised salbutamol","Urgent haemodialysis","Insulin-dextrose infusion","Calcium gluconate intravenously","Calcium resonium"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with mild hyperkalaemia (K+ 5.7 mmol/L) without ECG changes. Several factors may be contributing to her elevated potassium, including chronic kidney disease, diabetes, and medications (particularly ramipril).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium resonium \u003C/strong\u003Eis an appropriate first-line treatment for mild hyperkalaemia without ECG changes. It works by binding potassium in the gastrointestinal tract, promoting its excretion. This approach is suitable for gradual correction of potassium levels when urgent treatment is not required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium gluconate\u003C/strong\u003E is used for emergency cardiac membrane stabilisation in severe hyperkalaemia with ECG changes, which is not present in this case. It does not lower potassium levels but protects against cardiac arrhythmias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin-dextrose infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is typically reserved for moderate to severe hyperkalaemia (K+ \u0026gt;6.0 mmol/L) or when rapid reduction is needed. It works by driving potassium intracellularly but carries the risk of hypoglycaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent haemodialysis\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated for severe hyperkalaemia (K+ \u0026gt;6.5 mmol/L), life-threatening ECG changes, or refractory hyperkalaemia. This patient\u0027s mild elevation does not warrant such an aggressive intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENebulised salbutamol\u003C/strong\u003E can be used as an adjunct therapy in more severe cases of hyperkalaemia, working through beta-2 receptor stimulation to drive potassium intracellularly. However, it is not necessary as a first-line treatment for mild hyperkalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditionally, the underlying causes should be addressed by reviewing and potentially adjusting medications that can cause hyperkalaemia, ensuring adequate fluid status, and monitoring renal function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mild hyperkalaemia (K+ 5.5-5.9 mmol/L) without ECG changes can be managed with oral potassium binders.","The underlying cause of hyperkalaemia should always be identified and addressed.","Regular monitoring of potassium levels is essential when treating hyperkalaemia."],"references":["South Eastern Sydney Local Health District. Hyperkalaemia management in adults. SESLHDPR/282. 2016. Available at: https://www.seslhd.health.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/hyperkalaemia16.pdf","Simon LV, Hashmi MF, Farrell MW. Hyperkalemia. [Updated 2023 Sep 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470284/","Australian Medicines Handbook. Potassium disturbances. Australian Medicines Handbook Online. 2024. Available at: https://amhonline-amh-net-au.eu1.proxy.openathens.net/chapters/blood-electrolytes/drugs-electrolyte-imbalance/drugs-potassium-imbalance/potassium-disturbances#potassium-disturbances-01"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87232"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15809"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87232","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87232"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-05T10:18:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-05T10:18:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8500"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104846"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nu